---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const title = 'raucle Cloud — The graph and the audit export for your AI agents';
const description = 'AI agent security built to the standard regulated industries already demand for everything else — formal, mechanised, provable. Built on the open-source raucle-detect engine.';

// TODO: replace TALLY_FORM_ID with the form id from tally.so once the form is created.
const TALLY_FORM_ID = 'REPLACE_ME';

// TODO: set this to the city you want to show in the footer.
const LOCATION = 'REPLACE_ME';
---
<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <main>
    <header class="brand">
      <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <span>raucle</span>
    </header>

    <h1>The graph and the audit export for your AI agents.</h1>

    <p class="lede">
      Built on the open-source
      <a href="https://github.com/craigamcw/raucle-detect">raucle-detect</a>
      engine, with formal proofs you can hand to a regulator.
    </p>

    <h2>What it does</h2>
    <p>
      Drop in your agent. See every tool call it could be tricked into making.
      Get a PDF audit report — green nodes are mathematically safe, red nodes
      are open findings — that you hand to your FCA, BaFin, or EU AI Act
      examiner.
    </p>
    <p>
      Built for CISOs, Heads of AppSec, and GRC leads at fintechs and AI-native
      startups who need to prove their agents are safe before they touch real
      customer data.
    </p>

    <h2>Why this exists</h2>
    <p>
      AI agent security today is vendor heuristics and prompt-engineering
      folklore. None of it would survive the kind of scrutiny a payments
      system or a government workload gets. raucle is built to the standard
      regulated industries already demand for everything else — formal,
      mechanised, provable.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="label">Research</div>
      <p>
        <strong>Verified Capability Discipline for LLM Agent Tool Calls.</strong>
        Under submission to IEEE S&amp;P 2027. Branded preprint coming soon —
        <a href="mailto:hello@raucle.com?subject=Preprint%20request">request a copy</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>Status</h2>
    <div class="status-row">
      <div class="status-item">
        <span class="pill live">Live</span>
        <span>
          <strong>raucle-detect</strong> — the open-source engine. Active
          development at
          <a href="https://github.com/craigamcw/raucle-detect">github.com/craigamcw/raucle-detect</a>.
        </span>
      </div>
      <div class="status-item">
        <span class="pill soon">Soon</span>
        <span>
          <strong>raucle Cloud</strong> — the graph and the audit export.
          Private development. Join the waitlist for early access.
        </span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Join the waitlist</h2>
    <div class="waitlist">
      <iframe
        data-tally-src={`https://tally.so/embed/${TALLY_FORM_ID}?alignLeft=1&transparentBackground=1&dynamicHeight=1`}
        loading="lazy"
        width="100%"
        height="220"
        frameborder="0"
        marginheight="0"
        marginwidth="0"
        title="Join the raucle Cloud waitlist"
      ></iframe>
      <p class="fine">
        We'll only email you when there's something real to show. No marketing
        list, no drip campaign.
      </p>
    </div>

    <footer>
      <span>Built solo from {LOCATION}. © 2026 raucle.</span>
      <nav>
        <a href="https://github.com/craigamcw/raucle-detect">GitHub</a>
        <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/craigamcw/">LinkedIn</a>
      </nav>
    </footer>
  </main>

  <script
    is:inline
    async
    src="https://tally.so/widgets/embed.js"
  ></script>
</Base>
